title: For Sale:  Kel Tec KSG 12 Guage Shotgun 14+1 Bullpup Shotgun
postcontent: Kel Tec KSG 12 Guage Shotgun 14+1 Bullpup Shotgun For Sale. The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3". This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard. The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil. The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.

title: For Sale:  CZ 75D PCR with Two Holsters
postcontent:
The PCR name stands for ‘Police Czech Republic,’ the group for whom the model was originally designed. Nearly identical in size to the CZ 75 Compact, it weighs in at a full 1/4 pound lighter owing to its forged aluminum frame, making it more comfortable for everyday carry.

Equipped with a decocking lever, the PCR is designed to be decocked before holstering. After decocking, the trigger safety is much like that of a double action revolver. While there is no need to flip a safety lever off, the relatively longer and heavier trigger pull for the first round requires the conscious decision to pull the trigger before firing. Other additions to the PCR include rubber grip panels, serrated front and back straps for improved handling and a loaded chamber indicator.

title: For Sale:  Concealed Weapons Permit Classes
postcontent:
Concealed Weapons Permit Classes PENSACOLA.
The class is the NRA Basic Pistol / FL Concealed Weapons Permit class.  It covers safety, hands on classroom training, live fire training at the range, personal gun selection, cleaning/caring for a firearm and the laws/rules/procedures for the FL Concealed Weapons Permit. I also have a section of the class dedicated to personal defense with a firearm.  It is not necessary to own a firearm to attend the class as I have demo models.  If you own a firearm, I encourage you bring it to class so you can train with it.  We typically spend 3 to 3 1/2 hours in the classroom and about an hour on the range.  I hold the classes either at Homewood Suites Hotel Conference Room or Pensacola Indoor Shooting Range depending on availability.   My class is $85 per student and may be paid in cash, money order or local check.  Price includes class and all training materials.  Since we must complete live fire exercises there is an additional range fee of $15.  Additional charges apply if you wish to use a rental gun or purchase ammo.  Pensacola Indoor Shooting Range offers a large variety of rental guns if you wish to try out different models. Once you complete the class you will receive a certificate that satisfies the requirements for the FL CWP.  You then fill out an application, have your fingerprints and picture taken and submit the application.  The cost of the actual permit is $70 and the fingerprint / backround check is $42.  The permit is good for 7 years.

Here is a list of my current class schedule and registration link for them. You can register now and pay on the day of class.

title: For Sale:  Bohica Arms FAR50 MkIII .50 BMG AR upper - low round count
postcontent:
Up for sale is a Bohica Arms FAR50 MkIII .50 BMG AR upper in very good condition. Has the poly handguard and original bipod. The bipod had some rust and missing paint when I got this upper, I wire brushed and oiled it to prevent further rusting. There is no rust on the upper, 57 rounds fired through it total.

The MkIII is the one with the fixed firing pin, so don't be nervous about the crap on the internet about these. The MkII and older had a problem with a mushrooming firing pin that would jam and hangup. The newer one has a differently shaped firing pin and also hardened.

I'll be including the clearanced bolt catch (so you can use your lower for the .50 BMG and your normal upper, the .50 would hit a stock bho catch) and Wolf heavy hammer spring, as well as the billet scope rings it came with - they'll fit 1" or 30mm tubes.
